The sequence is initialized such that `x` values may contain duplicates, but `y` values are unique (corresponding to the original index), for example, generated using `parlay::tabulate(100000, [](int i) { UnstablePair val; val.x = (53 * i + 61) % 1024; val.y = i; return val; });`.

Sort this sequence in-place based on the `x` value in descending order, then `y` value in descending order for ties, using `parlay::internal::merge_sort_inplace` and `std::greater<UnstablePair>()` as the comparator.

output:
struct UnstablePair {
  int x, y;
  // Define operator> for std::greater<UnstablePair> to work.
  // This comparison sorts descending by x, then descending by y for ties.
  bool operator>(const UnstablePair& other) const {
      if (x != other.x) return x > other.x;
      return y > other.y;
  }
};

