Consider a type `NotTriviallyRelocatable` that holds an integer `x` and a pointer `px` pointing to `x`. This type is not trivially relocatable because a simple byte copy (like `memcpy`) would copy the original pointer value, making `px` in the new location point to the *old* location of `x`. We need to move an instance of this type from one uninitialized memory location to another using `parlay::relocate_at`.

```cpp
struct NotTriviallyRelocatable {
    int x;
    int* px;
    NotTriviallyRelocatable(int val) : x(val), px(&x) {}
    // A move constructor is needed for relocate_at to work correctly
    // for non-trivially relocatable types. It must update internal pointers.
    NotTriviallyRelocatable(NotTriviallyRelocatable&& other) noexcept : x(other.x) { px = &x; }
    // Destructor/Copy operations omitted for brevity
};
```

